'''''A-10 Tank Killer''''' is a 1989 [[Combat flight simulation game|combat flight simulation video game]] for [[DOS]] developed and published by [[Dynamix]]. An [[Amiga]] version was released in 1990. The game features an [[Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10 Thunderbolt II]] [[attack aircraft]]. Following the success of ''[[Red Baron (1990 video game)|Red Baron]]'', version 1.5 was released in 1991 which included [[Gulf War]] missions and improved graphics and sounds. Several mission packs were sold separately. A sequel published by [[Sierra Entertainment|Sierra]], ''[[Silent Thunder: A-10 Tank Killer II]]'', was released in 1996.

==Gameplay==
{{Expand section|date=April 2012}}
The gameplay consists of the player piloting an A-10 Thunderbolt II "tank killer" through various combat missions set in the [[Gulf War air campaign]] as well as a fictional European scenario. The player receives a mission briefing, has the opportunity to customize a weapon load-out before starting the mission, and is [[debriefing|debriefed]] after the mission.

==Reception==
According to Sierra On-Line, combined sales of ''A-10 Tank Killer'' and its sequel surpassed 250,000 units by the end of March 1996.<ref name="sierrasales">{{Cite report |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/724991/0000891020-96-000721.txt |title=Sierra On-Line Form 10-K |date=March 31, 1996 |location=Bellevue, Washington |pages=7–9 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416004925/https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/724991/0000891020-96-000721.txt |archive-date=April 16, 2018}}</ref>

''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' stated that "''A-10'' has much going for it" and gave it four stars out of five. The magazine recommended the game for those looking for quick fun, not "flight grognards" seeking realism.<ref name="brooks198912">{{Cite magazine |last=Brooks |first=M. Evan |date=December 1989 |title=Dynamix Takes to the Skies |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1989&pub=2&id=66 |magazine=Computer Gaming World |issue=66 |pages=42}}</ref><ref name="brooks199206">{{Cite magazine |last=Brooks |first=M. Evan |date=June 1992 |title=The Modern Games: 1950 - 2000 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1992&pub=2&id=95 |magazine=Computer Gaming World |pages=120 |accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> In a 1994 survey of wargames the magazine gave the title three-plus stars out of five, liking the graphics but noting the "very sensitive" joystick control.<ref name="brooks199401">{{Cite magazine |last=Brooks |first=M. Evan |date=January 1994 |title=War In Our Time / A Survey Of Wargames From 1950-2000 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=114 |magazine=Computer Gaming World |pages=194–212}}</ref> The DOS version of the game received 5 out of 5 stars in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]''.<ref name="Dragon176">{{Cite journal |last=Lesser |first=Hartley |last2=Lesser |first2=Patricia |last3=Lesser |first3=Kirk |name-list-style=amp |date=December 1991 |title=The Role of Computers |journal=Dragon |issue=176 |pages=57–62}}</ref> Because of the violence level of ''A-10 Tank Killer'', it has been placed on the "[[Federal Department for Media Harmful to Young Persons|Index]]" in Germany and is not generally available to the public.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Neueste INDEX-LISTE der BPjS in Bonn - Stand November 93 |url=http://www.ta7.de/txt/listen/list0012.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023140537/http://www.ta7.de/txt/listen/list0012.htm |archive-date=2009-10-23}}</ref>

